<h2 id="4howtoresolveconflicts">4️⃣ How to Resolve Conflicts</h2>
<h3 id="whatisamergeconflict"><strong>What is a Merge Conflict?</strong></h3>
<p><strong>Definition</strong>: 
A <strong>merge conflict</strong> occurs when Git cannot automatically merge changes because the same part of a file was modified in both branches.</p>
<h3 id="whenconflictsoccur"><strong>When Conflicts Occur</strong></h3>
<pre><code>CONFLICT SCENARIO:
──────────────────

Day 1:
main branch:      config.js → PORT = 3000

Day 2:
Developer A creates feature-A:
├─ Changes: PORT = 5000
└─ Merges to main ✓

Day 3:
Developer B creates feature-B (from old main):
├─ Changes: PORT = 8080
└─ Tries to merge → CONFLICT! ⚠️

Why? Same line changed in both branches!
Git doesn't know which to keep.
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h3 id="visualrepresentation"><strong>Visual Representation</strong></h3>
<pre><code>BEFORE CONFLICT:
────────────────

        A ← B ← C (main)
               ↗
              PORT = 3000

        MERGE feature-A:
        │
        ▼
        A ← B ← C ← D (main)
                    ↑
                  PORT = 5000


CONFLICT OCCURS:
────────────────

        A ← B ← C ← D (main, PORT = 5000)
               ↘
                E (feature-B, PORT = 8080)

        Try to merge feature-B:
                ↓
        ⚠️  CONFLICT! Same line different values
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h3 id="method1resolveingitlabwebui"><strong>Method 1: Resolve in GitLab Web UI</strong></h3>
<h4 id="stepbystep"><strong>Step-by-Step</strong></h4>
<pre><code>STEP 1: Conflict Detected
─────────────────────────

When creating or viewing MR:

┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ Merge request !42                                  │
├────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│                                                    │
│ ⚠️  This merge request has conflicts that must    │
│     be resolved                                    │
│                                                    │
│ Conflicting files:                                 │
│ ├─ config.js                                       │
│ └─ server.js                                       │
│                                                    │
│ [Resolve conflicts] [Resolve locally]              │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

Click [Resolve conflicts]


STEP 2: GitLab Conflict Editor
───────────────────────────────

┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ Resolve conflicts in config.js                        │
├────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│                                                        │
│ &lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt; feature-B (Your changes)                      │
│ const PORT = 8080;                                     │
│ =======                                                │
│ const PORT = 5000;                                     │
│ &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; main (Their changes)                          │
│                                                        │
│ [Use ours] [Use theirs] [Edit inline]                 │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘


STEP 3: Choose Resolution
──────────────────────────

Option 1: Use ours (feature-B version)
├─ Keeps: const PORT = 8080;

Option 2: Use theirs (main version)
├─ Keeps: const PORT = 5000;

Option 3: Edit inline (custom)
├─ Edit to: const PORT = process.env.PORT || 5000;


STEP 4: Commit Resolution
──────────────────────────

┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ All conflicts resolved                                 │
│                                                        │
│ Commit message:                                        │
│ ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────┐   │
│ │ Resolve conflicts in config.js                 │   │
│ │                                                 │   │
│ │ - Used environment variable for PORT           │   │
│ └────────────────────────────────────────────────┘   │
│                                                        │
│ [Commit to source branch]                              │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘


STEP 5: Merge Request Updated
──────────────────────────────

┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ Merge request !42                                      │
│                                                        │
│ ✅ All conflicts resolved                              │
│ ✅ Pipeline passed                                     │
│ ✅ Ready to merge                                      │
│                                                        │
│ [Merge]                                                │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h3 id="method2resolvelocally"><strong>Method 2: Resolve Locally</strong></h3>
<pre><code class="bash language-bash"># ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# RESOLVING CONFLICTS LOCALLY
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# STEP 1: Update your feature branch with latest main
$ git checkout feature-B
$ git fetch origin
$ git merge origin/main

Auto-merging config.js
CONFLICT (content): Merge conflict in config.js
Auto-merging server.js
CONFLICT (content): Merge conflict in server.js
Automatic merge failed; fix conflicts and then commit the result.


# STEP 2: Check status
$ git status

On branch feature-B
You have unmerged paths.
  (fix conflicts and run "git commit")

Unmerged paths:
  (use "git add &lt;file&gt;..." to mark resolution)
        both modified:   config.js
        both modified:   server.js


# STEP 3: View conflicts in file
$ cat config.js

const express = require('express');
&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt; HEAD
const PORT = 8080;  // Your changes (feature-B)
=======
const PORT = 5000;  // Their changes (main)
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; origin/main
const app = express();


# STEP 4: Edit file to resolve
$ vim config.js

# Manually edit to:
const express = require('express');
const PORT = process.env.PORT || 5000;  // Resolved
const app = express();

# Remove conflict markers (&lt;&lt;&lt;, ===, &gt;&gt;&gt;)


# STEP 5: Mark as resolved
$ git add config.js
$ git add server.js

$ git status
On branch feature-B
All conflicts fixed but you are still merging.
  (use "git commit" to conclude merge)


# STEP 6: Commit the resolution
$ git commit -m "Resolve merge conflicts

- Use environment variable for PORT
- Fallback to 5000 if not set
- Resolved conflicts in config.js and server.js"

[feature-B a1b2c3d] Resolve merge conflicts
 2 files changed, 5 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)


# STEP 7: Push to GitLab
$ git push origin feature-B

# MR automatically updates and shows conflicts resolved!
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h3 id="understandingconflictmarkers"><strong>Understanding Conflict Markers</strong></h3>
<pre><code>CONFLICT MARKERS EXPLAINED:
───────────────────────────

&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt; HEAD (or branch name)
YOUR CHANGES
These are your local changes
=======
THEIR CHANGES  
These are the incoming changes
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; branch-name (or commit hash)


REAL EXAMPLE:
─────────────

Original file (both branches started from here):
function greet() {
  console.log("Hello");
}

Branch A changed to:
function greet() {
  console.log("Hello World");
}

Branch B changed to:
function greet() {
  console.log("Hi there");
}

Conflict looks like:
function greet() {
&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt; feature-A
  console.log("Hello World");
=======
  console.log("Hi there");
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; feature-B
}


RESOLUTION OPTIONS:
───────────────────

Option 1: Keep feature-A version
function greet() {
  console.log("Hello World");
}

Option 2: Keep feature-B version
function greet() {
  console.log("Hi there");
}

Option 3: Combine both (if makes sense)
function greet(formal = false) {
  console.log(formal ? "Hello World" : "Hi there");
}

Option 4: Completely new solution
function greet() {
  console.log("Greetings!");
}
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h3 id="toolsforresolvingconflicts"><strong>Tools for Resolving Conflicts</strong></h3>
<h4 id="1gitlabwebeditorsimpleconflictsonly"><strong>1. GitLab Web Editor</strong> (Simple conflicts only)</h4>
<pre><code>Pros:
✅ No local setup needed
✅ Quick for simple conflicts
