Cons:
❌ Limited to simple conflicts
❌ Can't run tests
❌ No IDE features
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h4 id="2commandlinetexteditor"><strong>2. Command Line + Text Editor</strong></h4>
<pre><code class="bash language-bash"># Basic resolution
vim config.js
# Manually edit
git add config.js
git commit
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h4 id="3vscodebestformostcases"><strong>3. VS Code (Best for most cases)</strong></h4>
<pre><code>VS Code shows conflicts with actions:

┌────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ config.js                                      │
├────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│                                                │
│ &lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt; Current Change (feature-B)            │
│ const PORT = 8080;                             │
│ [Accept Current Change]                        │
│ =======                                        │
│ const PORT = 5000;                             │
│ [Accept Incoming Change]                       │
│ &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Incoming Change (main)                │
│ [Accept Both Changes] [Compare Changes]        │
│                                                │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

Click buttons or edit manually!
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h4 id="4gitkrakensourcetreeguitools"><strong>4. GitKraken / SourceTree (GUI Tools)</strong></h4>
<pre><code>Visual merge tool shows:

┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│          MERGE CONFLICT RESOLUTION                     │
├───────────────┬─────────────────┬──────────────────────┤
│   OURS        │    RESULT       │     THEIRS           │
│  (feature-B)  │   (Choose)      │    (main)            │
├───────────────┼─────────────────┼──────────────────────┤
│ PORT = 8080   │ PORT = 5000     │ PORT = 5000          │
│               │      ▲          │                      │
│               │   [Choose]      │                      │
│               │      │          │                      │
│ [Use this]    │   [Edit]        │ [Use this]           │
└───────────────┴─────────────────┴──────────────────────┘
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h3 id="bestpracticesforconflictresolution"><strong>Best Practices for Conflict Resolution</strong></h3>
<pre><code class="bash language-bash">✅ DO:
──────
1. Communicate with team
   "I'm resolving conflicts in config.js"

2. Understand both changes
   Read the diff, understand intent

3. Test after resolving
   Run tests before pushing

4. Keep commits atomic
   One logical change per commit

5. Pull frequently
   git pull origin main (daily)

6. Use descriptive commit messages
   "Resolve conflict: merge payment methods"

7. Ask for help
   If unsure, ask the other developer


❌ DON'T:
──────────
1. Blindly accept one side
   Understand what you're keeping/discarding

2. Resolve without testing
   Broken code might pass merge

3. Leave conflict markers
   Always remove &lt;&lt;&lt;, ===, &gt;&gt;&gt;

4. Mix resolution with new changes
   Conflict resolution commit should only resolve

5. Force push
   Never: git push --force (loses others' work)

6. Panic
   Conflicts are normal, take your time
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h3 id="complexconflictexample"><strong>Complex Conflict Example</strong></h3>
<pre><code class="javascript language-javascript">// ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// SCENARIO: Both developers modified authentication
// ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

// Original code (main):
function authenticate(username, password) {
  return users.find(u =&gt; u.name === username &amp;&amp; u.pass === password);
}

// Developer A (feature-A): Add email support
function authenticate(email, password) {
  return users.find(u =&gt; u.email === email &amp;&amp; u.pass === password);
}

// Developer B (feature-B): Add hashing
function authenticate(username, password) {
  const hashedPassword = hash(password);
  return users.find(u =&gt; u.name === username &amp;&amp; u.pass === hashedPassword);
}

// CONFLICT when merging:
function authenticate(
&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt; feature-A
email, password) {
  return users.find(u =&gt; u.email === email &amp;&amp; u.pass === password);
=======
username, password) {
  const hashedPassword = hash(password);
  return users.find(u =&gt; u.name === username &amp;&amp; u.pass === hashedPassword);
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; feature-B
}

// BEST RESOLUTION: Combine both features
function authenticate(identifier, password) {
  const hashedPassword = hash(password);
  return users.find(u =&gt; 
    (u.email === identifier || u.name === identifier) &amp;&amp; 
    u.pass === hashedPassword
  );
}

// Document in commit:
// "Resolve conflict: Support both email and username login with hashing"
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h2 id="5introductiontoide">5️⃣ Introduction to IDE</h2>
<h3 id="whatisanide"><strong>What is an IDE?</strong></h3>
<p><strong>Definition</strong>: 
An <strong>IDE (Integrated Development Environment)</strong> is a software application that provides comprehensive facilities to programmers for software development. It typically includes a code editor, debugger, build automation tools, and more.</p>
<h3 id="simpleanalogy-2"><strong>Simple Analogy</strong> 🛠️</h3>
<pre><code>Text Editor vs IDE:

Text Editor (Notepad, Vim):
├─ Like a basic toolbox
├─ Hammer, screwdriver
├─ Can build things but manually
└─ Simple, lightweight

IDE (VS Code, IntelliJ):
├─ Like a fully equipped workshop
├─ Power tools, workbench, organized storage
├─ Everything in one place
├─ Automation, suggestions, debugging
└─ Comprehensive, feature-rich
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h3 id="idevstexteditorvscodeeditor"><strong>IDE vs Text Editor vs Code Editor</strong></h3>
<pre><code>┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│         IDE vs CODE EDITOR vs TEXT EDITOR                │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

TEXT EDITOR              CODE EDITOR           IDE
───────────              ───────────           ───
Notepad                  VS Code               Visual Studio
Nano                     Sublime Text          IntelliJ IDEA
Vim                      Atom                  Eclipse
                         Notepad++             PyCharm
                                              WebStorm

Features:
├─ Basic editing        ├─ Syntax highlight   ├─ All code editor features
├─ Save files           ├─ Extensions         ├─ Built-in compiler
├─ Find/replace         ├─ Git integration    ├─ Debugger
└─ Minimal              ├─ Linting            ├─ Project management
                        ├─ Autocomplete       ├─ Database tools
                        └─ Terminal           ├─ Visual designer
                                              └─ Refactoring tools

Size:                   Size:                 Size:
&lt; 5 MB                  50-200 MB             500 MB - 2 GB

Speed:                  Speed:                Speed:
⚡ Very fast           ⚡ Fast               🐌 Can be slow

Use For:                Use For:              Use For:
Quick edits             General development   Large projects
Config files            Web development       Enterprise apps
Servers                 Multi-language        Complex debugging
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h3 id="keyidefeatures"><strong>Key IDE Features</strong></h3>
<pre><code>┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│              ESSENTIAL IDE FEATURES                      │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

1. CODE EDITOR
   ├─ Syntax highlighting (colors for code)
   ├─ Line numbers
   ├─ Code folding (collapse functions)
   ├─ Multiple cursors
   └─ Search &amp; replace

2. INTELLISENSE / AUTOCOMPLETE
   ├─ Suggests code as you type
   ├─ Parameter hints
   ├─ Auto-import
   └─ Documentation popup

3. DEBUGGING
   ├─ Breakpoints (pause execution)
   ├─ Step through code
   ├─ Watch variables
   ├─ Call stack
   └─ Console

4. VERSION CONTROL (Git)
   ├─ Visual diff
   ├─ Commit &amp; push from IDE
   ├─ Branch management
   ├─ Merge conflict resolution
   └─ Blame annotations

5. TERMINAL
   ├─ Built-in command line
   ├─ Multiple terminals
   ├─ Split view
   └─ Run commands without leaving IDE

6. EXTENSIONS/PLUGINS
   ├─ Add functionality
   ├─ Language support
   ├─ Themes
   └─ Productivity tools

7. PROJECT MANAGEMENT
   ├─ File explorer
   ├─ Search across files
   ├─ Refactoring tools
   └─ TODO tracking

8. LIVE PREVIEW
   ├─ See changes immediately
   ├─ Browser sync
   └─ Hot reload
</code></pre>
